'''Les Petites Bon-Bons''' was a group of [[Conceptual art|conceptual]]/life artists that originated in [[Milwaukee]], [[Wisconsin]], in the early 1970s. Their activities spanned the nascent [[Gay activism|gay activist movement]], the international correspondence network and the Hollywood [[Glam rock|glitter rock]] scene.<ref>Olds, Kristen. Art Journal, "Gay Life Artists: Les Petites Bonbons and Camp Performativity in the 1970s". June 1, 2013 p. 16-33.</ref> They are known largely by the work of [[Jerry Dreva]] and Robert Lambert, aka Jerry and Bobby Bonbon, and who achieved much of their fame by effectively manipulating major media outlets.<ref>Chavoya, C. Ondine and Frantz, David. "Axis Mundo: Queer Networks in Chicano L.A." Jan 30, 2018</ref>
==Early history== Les Petites Bon-Bons was originally coined as the name of a review to be staged by a group of young gay activist friends called the Radical Queens, veterans of the local Milwaukee counterculture and gay liberation scene, but it was never produced. In the hands of Dreva and Lambert, the group identity became a vehicle for the synthesis of art, politics, and sex that concerned them at the time.<ref>Burnham, Linda Frye. "High Performance, Have You Heard From Dreva?" Vol 3, no. 1 (Spring 1980) p.18-30</ref>
==Rock and Roll== Although other sub-identities became associated with the name, such as a fictional drum and bugle corps,<ref>Cameron, Daniel, "Extended Sensibilities: Homosexual Presence in Contemporary Art". The New Museum, 1982</ref> the Bon-Bons became known mainly as a conceptual rock band. Although they had no musical abilities and had never played a concert, Jerry and Bobby encouraged the notion among the rock journalists they befriended when they moved to Los Angeles, in June 1973 and January 1974, respectively.<ref>Reynolds, Simon "Shock and Awe: Glam Rock and Its Legacy, from the Seventies to the Twenty-first Century" Oct 11, 2016</ref> Personal links were formed with [[David Bowie]], [[Iggy Pop]], [[Lou Reed]], Sylvester and many others in the rock world.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}}
==Correspondence art== Dreva and Lambert had begun sending art projects to artists and writers they admired in early 1971, generating responses from noted critic [[Jack Burnham]], writer and gay activist [[Arthur Bell (journalist)|Arthur Bell]], and eventually generating an invitation to [[Richard Kostelanetz]]’s ASSEMBLING series,<ref>Kostelanetz, Richard, and Korn, Henry and Metz, Mike "Third Assembling". Assembling Press, Brooklyn, NY 1972</ref> through which they became aware of the formal network of international artists known as The Eternal Network. These included [[Ray Johnson]], the Western Front, [[General Idea]] and [[FILE Megazine|FILE megazine]], Clemente Padin in Uruguay and COUM/[[Throbbing Gristle]] in the UK.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=p4HkDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT141&lpg=PT141&dq=Jerry+and+Bobby+Bonbon&source=bl&ots=8lBJMWOZl7&sig=nc9UePWTpVLrv-DbhSVEEg8YGF8&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwitw7_92ODbAhUr_4MKHSzsBBwQ6AEIQzAI#v=onepage&q=Jerry%20and%20Bobby%20Bonbon&f=false|title=Art Sex Music|last=Tutti|first=Cosey Fanni|date=2017-04-04|publisher=Faber & Faber|isbn=9780571328543|language=en}}</ref>
